Adult Exploration / BSR / OSR

We have more males than females every season (in this analysis).

I will need to go back and look at which female nest failed and how many females we lost in sequencing to get better picture of the breeding sex ratios. Our goal was to sequence every nest from every female over all four years but we may have lost a females nest, excluding her from these calculations.

## BRAZIL S1: 19F, 35M
## BRAZIL S2: 25F, 50M
## BRAZIL S3: 39F, 63M
## BRAZIL S4: 44F, 71M

The breeding sex ratio is calculated as the #Males/#Females that actually contribute to reproduction in a population.

We get a breeding sex ratio of 1.42 meaning tha are about 1.4x breeding males as females.

The Operation Sex Ratio is calculated as the percentage of males in the breeding population: males/(males+females) 100.

  • We have a male biases OSR (>50%) which would typically lead to increased male-male competition.
## Overall breeding sex ratio: 1.42 (175 males : 123 females)
## Operational sex ratio: 58.7% males
## Season S1 breeding sex ratio: 1.84 (35 males : 19 females)
## Operational sex ratio: 64.8% males
## Season S2 breeding sex ratio: 2 (50 males : 25 females)
## Operational sex ratio: 66.7% males
## Season S3 breeding sex ratio: 1.62 (63 males : 39 females)
## Operational sex ratio: 61.8% males
## Season S4 breeding sex ratio: 1.61 (71 males : 44 females)
## Operational sex ratio: 61.7% males

The effective population size is calculated by Ne = (4 * Nm * Nf) / (Nm + Nf). Need to check with literature that this is the correct eqn.

We have an effective population size of 288. It would be interesting to compare this to other populations.

Investigating males from multiple seasons:

  • Proportional Success: fraction of the total offspring in a given season were sired by a particular male. It shows a males reproductive success relative to all other males in that season. A higher value means the male sired a larger percentage of all offspring in that season.
  • Reproductive efficiency: How many offspring a male produces per mate. A higher value means the male produces more offspring per female mate on average.

From the wilcox test, theres no real stat differences between male reproductive metrics between seasons. This helps us answer Do males tend to become more or less successful (or efficient) between consecutive breeding seasons? and we get the answer of no.

## 
## Season-to-season success transitions using relative metrics:
## From S1 to S2 (5 males):
##   Proportional success: 2 increased, 3 decreased, 2 remained similar
##   Reproductive efficiency: 4 increased, 1 decreased, 0 remained similar
##   Proportional success Wilcoxon p-value: 1 (no significant difference)
##   Reproductive efficiency Wilcoxon p-value: 0.2785 (no significant difference)
##   Rank correlation between seasons: rho = 0.4, p = 0.5167 (no significant correlation)
